---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Nigeria Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/nigeria/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Ghana for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/ghana' },
  { title: 'Kenya for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/kenya' },
  { title: 'South Africa for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/south-africa' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'nigeriaFit', header: 'Nigeria Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'NGN$675,000-965,000/mo', nigeriaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'NGN$790,000-1.13M/mo', nigeriaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: 'NGN$607,500-868,000/mo', nigeriaFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'AXA Mansard (Local)', entryAge: '65', renewal: 'Varies', monthlyFrom: 'NGN$100,000-300,000/mo', nigeriaFit: 'Limited' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: 'NGN$607,500-965,000', annual: 'NGN$7.29M-11.58M' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: 'NGN$833,000-1.29M', annual: 'NGN$10M-15.5M' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: 'NGN$1.12M-1.73M', annual: 'NGN$13.4M-20.7M' },
  { category: 'Private Hospital Visit (Lagos)', monthly: 'NGN$30,000-100,000/visit', annual: 'Variable' },
  { category: 'Evacuation to London/Dubai', monthly: 'N/A', annual: 'NGN$30M-100M' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Nigeria 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors in Nigeria. Africa's largest economy, family connections, security concerns, and coverage for diaspora retirees 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Nigeria"
  subheadline="Nigeria offers Africa's largest economy, vibrant Lagos culture, family diaspora connections, and growing economy—primarily for those with family ties or professional reasons, with significant security and healthcare considerations."
  heroImage="/images/countries/nigeria-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Important: Nigeria Is Complex</h2>
  <p>
    Nigeria is Africa's most populous country and largest economy. Primarily chosen by those with Nigerian family connections, business interests, or professional reasons. Significant security concerns in many areas, healthcare limitations, and infrastructure challenges make it unsuitable for typical Western retirement.
  </p>

  <p>
    Lagos is economic hub with best healthcare. Abuja is capital with more security. Port Harcourt is oil industry center. Population 220+ million. London (6 hours) and Dubai (7 hours) provide medical backup for complex cases.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-red-900 mb-3">Security Considerations</h3>
    <ul class="text-red-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Crime:</strong> High in urban areas; armed robbery, carjacking</li>
      <li><strong>Kidnapping:</strong> Risk in various regions</li>
      <li><strong>Northern Nigeria:</strong> Serious security concerns (Boko Haram)</li>
      <li><strong>Niger Delta:</strong> Oil-related conflict areas</li>
      <li><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Only with strong local connections and security</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Nigeria Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Nigeria healthcare is variable—good private hospitals in Lagos (St. Nicholas Hospital, Lagoon Hospital) and Abuja serve wealthy Nigerians and expats. Public healthcare underfunded. Complex cases often go to London, Dubai, or India for treatment. "Medical tourism" outbound is common for wealthy Nigerians.
  </p>

  <p>
    Lagos has best private options. Abuja has some quality care. Outside major cities, healthcare very limited. International insurance with strong evacuation coverage essential.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">International Evacuation Common</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      Wealthy Nigerians regularly fly to London, Dubai, or India for complex medical care. Lagos private hospitals good for routine care. Include UK/UAE/India in insurance coverage. Don't rely solely on local healthcare for serious conditions.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options</h2>
  <p>
    Nigeria visa options:
  </p>

  <h3>Tourist Visa</h3>
  <p>
    Required for most nationalities. Apply through Nigerian embassy. 90-day maximum.
  </p>

  <h3>Business Visa</h3>
  <p>
    For business activities. Various categories and durations.
  </p>

  <h3>Subject to Regularization (STR)</h3>
  <p>
    For temporary residence. Work or family basis.
  </p>

  <h3>Nigerian Diaspora</h3>
  <p>
    Dual citizenship available. Many diaspora Nigerians return after retirement with existing citizenship.
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance requirements for Nigeria:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Entry:</strong> Travel insurance strongly recommended</li>
    <li><strong>Extended stay:</strong> International coverage essential</li>
    <li><strong>Evacuation:</strong> UK/Dubai/India coverage critical</li>
    <li><strong>Security:</strong> Consider security evacuation coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for Nigeria</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      Comprehensive international insurance with UK, Dubai, and India evacuation coverage essential. Lagos private hospitals handle routine needs. Include security evacuation consideration. Premium coverage recommended.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in Nigeria, international evacuation coverage critical:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3>Why These Providers Work for Nigeria</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Strong global network, UK access</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA Global:</strong> Highest entry age (79), comprehensive</li>
    <li><strong>UK access:</strong> Common evacuation destination</li>
    <li><strong>Dubai/India:</strong> Alternative medical hubs</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Get Personalized Senior Quotes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Compare coverage for Nigeria with international evacuation.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for Nigeria (NGN ~1,500 to USD):
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3>Cost Considerations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Premium coverage:</strong> Essential for security and healthcare</li>
    <li><strong>Lagos private:</strong> Quality but expensive locally</li>
    <li><strong>International evacuation:</strong> Budget for overseas care</li>
    <li><strong>Security costs:</strong> Compound living, drivers add expense</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 1: Returning Diaspora, 68</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $5,000/month pension. Family in Lagos. Nigerian citizenship.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Cigna Global with UK and Nigeria coverage.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~NGN$750,000/month (~$500). Family support; London backup.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 2: Business Retiree, 66</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $7,000/month. Oil industry background. Abuja compound.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> BUPA Global with security coverage.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~NGN$850,000/month (~$565). Industry connections; comprehensive.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 3: NOT Recommended</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Western retiree without Nigerian connections.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Consider Ghana, Kenya, or South Africa instead.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Reality:</strong> Security and complexity make Nigeria unsuitable without strong local ties.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can Westerners retire to Nigeria?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Not recommended unless Nigerian diaspora or strong business/family ties. Security challenges, healthcare limitations, and infrastructure issues make it impractical for typical Western retirement. Those who live there typically have compound security and international evacuation plans.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Lagos safe?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Relatively safe in wealthy areas with precautions—compound living, drivers, security. Traffic is major challenge. Armed robbery exists. Most expats live in secure compounds (Ikoyi, Victoria Island). Normal life possible but requires security awareness.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why do Nigerians go abroad for healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Common practice—wealthy Nigerians regularly fly to London, Dubai, India for complex care. Local private hospitals good but limited specialists. "Medical tourism" outbound is normal. International insurance facilitating this access is essential.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Are there safer African alternatives?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Yes—Ghana (similar culture, safer), Kenya (wildlife, better tourism), South Africa (developed infrastructure). All have their own challenges but less security concerns than Nigeria. Consider these for African experience without Nigerian complexity.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Consider Safer Alternatives</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Similar African experience with better conditions.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/insurance-for/seniors/in/ghana" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Ghana Guide</a>
      <a href="/insurance-for/seniors/in/south-africa" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">South Africa Guide</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> Nigeria presents significant security and healthcare challenges. NOT recommended for typical Western retirement. Only suitable for those with strong Nigerian connections and security arrangements. Always check current travel advisories.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
